Europe
------
[1] The Netherlands (RIVM report)
Date: Wed 16 Oct 2013
Source: RIVM (National Institute for Public Health and the Environment) report [edited]
http://www.rivm.nl/en/Topics/M/Measles


Measles in the Netherlands from 1 May to 16 Oct 2013
----------------------------------------------------
An outbreak of measles is on going in the Netherlands, mostly situated in municipalities with a low level of vaccination coverage (under 90 per cent). It is expected that this virus will spread in these areas among unvaccinated children in the coming period. Children below 14 months of age with an increased risk of contracting measles will be offered an extra vaccination against measles, mumps and rubella (MMR vaccine). In general, the Dutch population is well protected against measles because of vaccination or immunity from having had the disease.

Measles outbreak
----------------
Since the end of May [2013], cases of measles are being reported in a number of areas. The epidemic is spreading, especially in communities where vaccination coverage is low (less than 90 per cent). Many of the people living in these areas belong to the Dutch Orthodox Reformed Church. For religious reasons they do not have their children vaccinated. It is likely that the disease will spread further because a relatively large number of children in these areas are not protected against measles.

Earlier this year [2013], there were several local outbreaks in The Hague, Alblasserwaard and the Land of Heusden and Altena region. The National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM) is in very close contact with the community health services (GGDs) in question. Doctors in the areas concerned have been informed.

Effect of vaccination
---------------------
In the Netherlands, there has been a large decrease in the number of patients with measles and the number of deaths since measles vaccination was introduced into the Dutch National Vaccination Program in 1976. The vaccination is at least 95 per cent effective. Measles epidemics occur periodically among the population groups who are not vaccinated. The last outbreak in the Netherlands was between 1999 and 2000 when there were 150 children with measles admitted to a hospital and 3 children died from the effects of the disease.

--
