[4] Canada (Alberta)
Date: Tue 22 Oct 2013
Source: Global News [summ., edited]
http://globalnews.ca/news/919376/health-officials-urge-parents-to-vaccinate-following-measles-outbreak/


Health officials in Lethbridge are preparing for what could be a major outbreak of measles, and have erected a number of tents outside the Chinook Regional Hospital to serve as a measles assessment clinic. "We know there's a large population out there, hundreds of people actually have already been exposed based on information we've received and who are not immune," says Dr Vivian Suttorp, the South Zone medical officer of health for Alberta Health Services.

On Friday [18 Oct 2013], AHS officials confirmed a single case of measles in the south zone. The boy is a Grade 9 student at Coaldale Christian School. "He went home sick," Joop Harthoorn, the school's principal says. "At the time we were not aware it was measles." Alberta Health also notified the school late last week, and a notice was sent home to parents on Monday [21 Oct 2013]. According to Dr Martin Lavoie, Alberta's deputy chief medical officer of health, the student contracted the illness on a recent trip to the Netherlands. "We know he went to school, to church and a hockey game before we identified the illness so it is likely we will see more cases of the disease."

Measles is a highly contagious respiratory illness that begins with mild cold and flu-like symptoms. After 4 to 7 days, patients may experience a high fever before developing a rash. The rash usually begins behind the ears before spreading to the face, down the body and to the arms and legs. "People are contagious up to 4 days after the start of the rash, but interestingly enough people will be contagious and spreading illness before they have any symptoms," Suttorp explains. Health officials have quarantined individuals they believe have been exposed, asking anyone who may have come in contact with the boy to stay home for 21 days.

Measles immunization clinics are also set to begin in Lethbridge on Wednesday [23 Oct 2013]. Infants usually receive the 1st of 2 doses of the measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine at 12 months but during this outbreak infants 6-to-12 months can also receive a dose.

The MMR vaccination rate across Alberta is 84 per cent, far below the 98 per cent needed to achieve herd immunity. In areas around Lethbridge, the rate is less than 70 per cent. Health officials say vaccination rates have been dropping in recent years and Alberta Health is currently working on plan to try and reverse this trend. "Some parents are choosing not to vaccinate their children based on misinformation," says Lavoie. "We are very concerned about this."

[byline: Heather Yourex and Stefanie Dunn]

--
communicated by:
