[7] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Wed 23 Oct 2013
Source: The Queensland Times [edited]
http://www.qt.com.au/news/doctor-confirms-a-12th-case-of-measles-in-city/2060391/


A 12th measles case has been confirmed in Ipswich [Queensland]. West Moreton Hospital and Health Service public health physician Dr Kari Jarvinen said an unknowingly infectious man caught the 4:40pm train from East Ipswich station to Booval station last Thursday [17 Oct 2013], then walked through Booval Fair. "To date 11 of the 12 confirmed measles cases in Ipswich had occurred in adults who were born after 1966," Dr Jarvinen said.

"Many adults in their late 20s and early 30s mistakenly believe that they have been vaccinated for measles as a child when in fact they haven't. "This may be because measles vaccine wasn't universally available to all children in Australia until the late 1980s and early 1990s. "Adults born in 1966 or later and who do not have documentation of having received measles vaccine, or having had the infection are particularly at risk of contracting the disease, in the current outbreak setting. "If you are unsure of your measles immunity or vaccination status, please talk to your GP."

